Dialogue: 0,00:39:22.880,00:39:27.440,辉英,,0,0,0,,look a lot like each other as you go to higher order. So if I
Dialogue: 0,00:39:27.440,00:39:31.420,辉英,,0,0,0,,told you about I have this set of vectors, and they're starting
Dialogue: 0,00:39:31.420,00:39:32.920,辉英,,0,0,0,,to look more and more like each other.
Dialogue: 0,00:39:33.280,00:39:36.280,辉英,,0,0,0,,And as I get more and more of these vectors, I kind of want to
Dialogue: 0,00:39:36.280,00:39:38.960,辉英,,0,0,0,,come up with some way of figuring out how much of each of these
Dialogue: 0,00:39:38.960,00:39:42.580,辉英,,0,0,0,,vectors to use. What scheme would you do to try to make to be able
Dialogue: 0,00:39:42.580,00:39:47.980,辉英,,0,0,0,,to tease those different pieces apart? So I have a set of vectors
Dialogue: 0,00:39:47.980,00:39:50.200,辉英,,0,0,0,,and they're almost linearly dependent. And I want to turn
Dialogue: 0,00:39:50.200,00:39:54.520,辉英,,0,0,0,,them into something that is as close to orthogonal as possible.
Dialogue: 0,00:39:55.220,00:40:02.120,辉英,,0,0,0,,What scheme would I use? So I have a set of columns of a
Dialogue: 0,00:40:02.120,00:40:02.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,matrix, and I want to make a column of a matrix. And I want to
Dialogue: 0,00:40:02.860,00:40:03.200,辉英,,0,0,0,,make a column of a matrix. And I want to make a column of a matrix.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:03.280,00:40:03.640,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to call the vector in this case. And when I call the
Dialogue: 0,00:40:03.640,00:40:03.920,辉英,,0,0,0,,vector of a matrix, I'm going to call it a set of columns orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:40:03.920,00:40:07.940,辉英,,0,0,0,,to each other. What do I do? Same person invented this algorithm
Dialogue: 0,00:40:07.940,00:40:17.300,辉英,,0,0,0,,invented some kind of cracker, Graham Schmidt. Remember Graham
Dialogue: 0,00:40:17.300,00:40:24.840,辉英,,0,0,0,,Schmidt orthogonalization? No. All right, so then we're not going
Dialogue: 0,00:40:24.840,00:40:27.580,辉英,,0,0,0,,to worry about when we calculate these polynomials, but let's,
Dialogue: 0,00:40:27.580,00:40:31.380,辉英,,0,0,0,,for a moment, assume that we could come up with orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:40:31.380,00:40:32.220,辉英,,0,0,0,,polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:33.280,00:40:35.220,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're going to pick some other set of polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:35.340,00:40:36.920,辉英,,0,0,0,,We don't like the monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:37.340,00:40:39.840,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're instead, because the monomials start to look like each other,
Dialogue: 0,00:40:40.240,00:40:41.800,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we're going to decide that instead,
Dialogue: 0,00:40:42.160,00:40:44.440,辉英,,0,0,0,,we're going to come up with polynomials that have a certain property.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:46.580,00:40:47.360,辉英,,0,0,0,,So instead,
Dialogue: 0,00:40:48.140,00:40:53.240,辉英,,0,0,0,,we're going to try to come up with polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:40:53.240,00:40:56.040,辉英,,0,0,0,,that are very different from each other.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:56.520,00:40:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're going to define very different as something like this.
Dialogue: 0,00:40:59.860,00:41:04.000,辉英,,0,0,0,,We have a c i of x, a c j of x,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:04.360,00:41:06.760,辉英,,0,0,0,,integrated over the central point from 0 to 1,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:07.680,00:41:10.240,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we want it to be equal to x,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:10.320,00:41:11.980,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we want that to be equal to 0
Dialogue: 0,00:41:11.980,00:41:15.320,辉英,,0,0,0,,if i is not equal to j.
Dialogue: 0,00:41:17.060,00:41:18.840,辉英,,0,0,0,,This is orthogonality.
Dialogue: 0,00:41:25.080,00:41:28.580,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you've seen how little in trying to construct basic functions of the orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:41:28.580,00:41:29.840,辉英,,0,0,0,,can give you better conditions.
Dialogue: 0,00:41:29.860,00:41:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You can't do the same thing with condition systems
Dialogue: 0,00:41:31.860,00:41:34.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,when you do a basis function based discretization of PDEs.
Dialogue: 0,00:41:34.860,00:41:40.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But you also have it in a very much simpler setting.
Dialogue: 0,00:41:40.860,00:41:42.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're doing the same thing,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:42.860,00:41:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if I took these polynomials and sampled them,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:45.860,00:41:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I would get a vector,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:47.860,00:41:50.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then we're still talking about trying to make these two vectors orthogonal to each other.
Dialogue: 0,00:41:50.860,00:41:54.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So it doesn't matter whether you think of this as a polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:54.860,00:41:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,two polynomials who want to make orthogonal to each other,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:57.860,00:41:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or you think of representing them as a vector,
Dialogue: 0,00:41:59.860,00:42:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but you're actually going to be using a function with points,
Dialogue: 0,00:42:01.860,00:42:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we're trying to say the two vectors,
Dialogue: 0,00:42:03.860,00:42:06.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,like the picture we drew here.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:06.860,00:42:08.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If we think of these as vectors,
Dialogue: 0,00:42:08.860,00:42:12.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we're now going to end up with vectors whose inner product is going to be 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:13.860,00:42:16.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And now how are we going to construct those polynomials?
Dialogue: 0,00:42:16.860,00:42:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, I'll come back.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:20.860,00:42:22.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Let's pretend we have them first.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:22.860,00:42:24.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Suppose we could construct polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:24.860,00:42:26.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So here's one, right?
Dialogue: 0,00:42:26.860,00:42:28.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So it's the polynomial 1, all 1s,
Dialogue: 0,00:42:28.860,00:42:30.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the polynomial x.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:30.860,00:42:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Are they orthogonal to each other?
Dialogue: 0,00:42:33.860,00:42:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If I take the inner product of 1 and x and integrate it from 0 to 1,
Dialogue: 0,00:42:37.860,00:42:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,are those two orthogonal to each other?
Dialogue: 0,00:42:39.860,00:42:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Not at all.
Dialogue: 0,00:42:41.860,00:42:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Can you give me a polynomial that has a first order and a zeroth order term
Dialogue: 0,00:42:45.860,00:42:48.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that is orthogonal to 1?
Dialogue: 0,00:42:52.860,00:42:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I have 1,
Dialogue: 0,00:42:55.860,00:42:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and...
Dialogue: 0,00:42:58.860,00:43:08.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So give me a polynomial that involves x,
Dialogue: 0,00:43:08.860,00:43:10.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but is orthogonal to 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:10.860,00:43:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,1 minus 2x.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:13.860,00:43:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,1 minus 2x.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:15.860,00:43:18.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I've got to put a sign in the x.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:18.860,00:43:20.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So suppose I wrote down,
Dialogue: 0,00:43:20.860,00:43:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if I have x and I'm going from 0 to 1,
Dialogue: 0,00:43:23.860,00:43:26.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I want its inner product to be 0 with 1,
Dialogue: 0,00:43:26.860,00:43:28.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,what am I going to subtract off?
Dialogue: 0,00:43:28.860,00:43:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So what you said is exactly right.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:33.860,00:43:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You said it.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:35.860,00:43:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But I'm going to scale it slightly differently.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:37.860,00:43:40.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I have x. It goes from 0 to 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:40.860,00:43:42.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And I now want it to be orthogonal to 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:42.860,00:43:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And I take the inner product of the constant
Dialogue: 0,00:43:47.860,00:43:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,with something that's linear.
Dialogue: 0,00:43:49.860,00:43:52.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What do I want to make this linear function do
Dialogue: 0,00:43:52.860,00:43:56.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so that the inner product of these two is a constant?
Dialogue: 0,00:43:56.860,00:43:58.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Excuse me, 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:04.860,00:44:06.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What should this function be?
Dialogue: 0,00:44:06.860,00:44:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It's got to have the x in it,
Dialogue: 0,00:44:07.860,00:44:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because it's got to be in my mind.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:09.860,00:44:10.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What should I do with it?
Dialogue: 0,00:44:10.860,00:44:12.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,All I've got to do is shift it somewhere.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:12.860,00:44:14.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Where?
Dialogue: 0,00:44:14.860,00:44:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If I take this point at a half,
Dialogue: 0,00:44:17.860,00:44:20.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and make sure it goes through the half,
Dialogue: 0,00:44:20.860,00:44:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,are these two orthogonal to each other?
Dialogue: 0,00:44:23.860,00:44:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I got this one.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:26.860,00:44:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The second one, by taking the 0th order polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:44:31.860,00:44:36.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and subtracting some fraction of it off the first order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:36.860,00:44:38.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So now you can do that scheme.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:38.860,00:44:40.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You can do a second order polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:44:40.860,00:44:42.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,by starting with x squared
Dialogue: 0,00:44:42.860,00:44:44.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then subtracting whatever it takes
Dialogue: 0,00:44:44.860,00:44:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to make the x squared orthogonal to the first order polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:44:47.860,00:44:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and subtracting off whatever makes it x squared orthogonal to the constant polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:51.860,00:44:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we can construct polynomials this way.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:53.860,00:44:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But I'm not going to worry so much about that at the moment.
Dialogue: 0,00:44:56.860,00:45:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Let's presume that we can figure out how to do that.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:03.860,00:45:08.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So suppose we recast our exact instance constraint
Dialogue: 0,00:45:08.860,00:45:10.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,with these orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:10.860,00:45:12.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, we have, we can't just pick any polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:12.860,00:45:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,They have to have, the 0th order polynomial has to have
Dialogue: 0,00:45:15.860,00:45:18.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the monomials, the x to the 0 monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:18.860,00:45:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The first order one has to have the x1 monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:21.860,00:45:24.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The second order one has to have the x squared monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:24.860,00:45:26.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But other than that, they can have whatever way
Dialogue: 0,00:45:26.860,00:45:28.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to do the combination of lower order polynomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:45:28.860,00:45:30.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,lower order monomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:45:30.860,00:45:32.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to make them orthogonal to each other.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:32.860,00:45:34.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we imagine then saying,
Dialogue: 0,00:45:34.860,00:45:38.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,alright, we started out with n monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:38.860,00:45:42.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or, excuse me, 2n monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:42.860,00:45:50.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or the 0th order 1 plus all the way to order 2n minus 1 in monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:50.860,00:45:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we have our 2n constraints starting from the complex term
Dialogue: 0,00:45:53.860,00:45:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,all the way to the 0th order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:45:55.860,00:45:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're going to replace those monomial constraints
Dialogue: 0,00:45:59.860,00:46:04.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,with constraints using these orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:04.860,00:46:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It should be, because it should be good enough.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:09.860,00:46:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I mean, any set of polynomials, as long as we can guarantee
Dialogue: 0,00:46:13.860,00:46:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that we can write down any polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:46:15.860,00:46:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,away the combination of this orthogonal set,
Dialogue: 0,00:46:17.860,00:46:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which you can, you can certainly, each of these is involving monomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:21.860,00:46:24.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we can put them together in ways to make the,
Dialogue: 0,00:46:24.860,00:46:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you know, whatever polynomial we want.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:27.860,00:46:30.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we have certainly covered our constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:30.860,00:46:34.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But now we're putting it in terms of these orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:34.860,00:46:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So, an 0th order polynomial still has to have x to the lth power.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:39.860,00:46:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But it could have any of the lower order terms.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:41.860,00:46:44.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And because of that, we can represent any polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:46:44.860,00:46:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,with a weighted combination of these orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:47.860,00:46:50.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we can rewrite our constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:50.860,00:46:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Is this going to make our problem any easier?
Dialogue: 0,00:46:53.860,00:46:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We still have two n constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:46:57.860,00:47:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Are these now constraints, are they now linear?
Dialogue: 0,00:47:03.860,00:47:06.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, you know, because I've got,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:06.860,00:47:10.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I put the x's inside the c functions.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:10.860,00:47:12.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So doesn't that make the problem linear?
Dialogue: 0,00:47:12.860,00:47:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,No, of course not.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:15.860,00:47:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It may be a little more hidden,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:17.860,00:47:20.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but they still have the products of weights times polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:20.860,00:47:22.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,They're just more complicated polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:22.860,00:47:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If anything, it seems like it makes it harder.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:25.860,00:47:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Because the original ones might have the,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:27.860,00:47:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the Lth constraint had one weight times only a coefficient times x to the l.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:33.860,00:47:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And now it's got all these other terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:35.860,00:47:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the x to the l minus 1, the l minus 2.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:37.860,00:47:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It seems like we're making it worse.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:39.860,00:47:42.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,All right, so,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:42.860,00:47:46.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if we have these orthogonal polynomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:46.860,00:47:50.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and this notion of orthogonal for polynomials is,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:50.860,00:47:52.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we say, that inner product of,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:52.860,00:47:54.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of two polynomials is equal to zero,
Dialogue: 0,00:47:54.860,00:47:56.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if they're of different order.
Dialogue: 0,00:47:56.860,00:48:00.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we sometimes use this inner product notation,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:00.860,00:48:04.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or we use rectangular brackets, or,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:04.860,00:48:06.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but it's the same idea as taking two vectors
Dialogue: 0,00:48:06.860,00:48:08.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and looking at their inner product.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:08.860,00:48:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And if we sampled the polynomials and constructed the vectors that way,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:11.860,00:48:14.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it would turn out to be identically the same thing.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:14.860,00:48:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or, you know, if we did this by quadrature,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:17.860,00:48:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,well, we'll get to that.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:19.860,00:48:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:21.860,00:48:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,imagine now we do the following.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:25.860,00:48:28.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We rewrite the exactness constraints,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:28.860,00:48:30.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we do it for the first half of the terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:30.860,00:48:32.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,what we'll call the lower terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:32.860,00:48:34.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from zero to n minus 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:34.860,00:48:38.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We'll write those in terms of these n minus 1 orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:38.860,00:48:40.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And then for the higher terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:40.860,00:48:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we're going to write them a little bit differently.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:43.860,00:48:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,These are the terms that have to do with cn through c to the 2n minus 1 polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:49.860,00:48:50.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we've got the lower terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:50.860,00:48:52.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from zero to n minus 1,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:52.860,00:48:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the higher terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:48:53.860,00:48:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from n to 2n minus 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:55.860,00:48:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're just breaking them in half.
Dialogue: 0,00:48:59.860,00:49:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Now these higher order terms,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:01.860,00:49:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we don't have to generate these additional polynomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:05.860,00:49:08.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the nth order and the 2n minus 1 order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:08.860,00:49:10.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We could do something different.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:10.860,00:49:12.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We could instead say,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:12.860,00:49:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,well, if I want an nth order polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:15.860,00:49:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,an n plus 1 order polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:17.860,00:49:18.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or an nth order polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:18.860,00:49:20.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I could take c to the n,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:20.860,00:49:24.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I could just multiply by c of 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:24.860,00:49:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's still c of 0 as a 0th order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:27.860,00:49:28.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If I multiply it by an nth order polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:28.860,00:49:30.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it's still nth order.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:30.860,00:49:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But when I get all the way up to a 2n minus 1 polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:49:33.860,00:49:36.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I could have written it down as the product of the nth order polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:49:36.860,00:49:40.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,times the n minus 1 order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:40.860,00:49:46.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Will this product still have a term that's x to the 2n minus 1?
Dialogue: 0,00:49:46.860,00:49:50.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The highest order term in the cn polynomial will be x to the n.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:50.860,00:49:54.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The product of the 2 will be x to the 2n minus 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:54.860,00:49:58.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's all we're using.
Dialogue: 0,00:49:58.860,00:50:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we also know that the products are independent of each other.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:03.860,00:50:06.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Because we know that when we do,
Dialogue: 0,00:50:06.860,00:50:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because we know something about cn times c of 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:09.860,00:50:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So these are different from the lower order polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:13.860,00:50:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So now we're going to look at the product of the nth order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:17.860,00:50:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're going to look at the product of the nth order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:19.860,00:50:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So now we have yet another way of writing our exactness constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:23.860,00:50:26.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And this is the really amazing thing.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:26.860,00:50:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If we write our exactness constraints to the high order polynomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:50:33.860,00:50:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we're using orthogonal polynomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:50:37.860,00:50:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then these and their products really should all be 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:41.860,00:50:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Because if we integrate, these terms are all 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:45.860,00:50:48.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Because they're orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:48.860,00:50:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I'm using products.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:49.860,00:50:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So the actual integral we're trying to match.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:51.860,00:50:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But that doesn't mean our quadrature scheme produces 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:55.860,00:50:58.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But it gives us a very simple thing to evaluate.
Dialogue: 0,00:50:58.860,00:51:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Now the question is, how do we make sure that our quadrature scheme produces 0s?
Dialogue: 0,00:51:05.860,00:51:10.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we know for the high order terms, the integrals we're using to test all have the integral 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:10.860,00:51:14.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Because they're integrals of the products of orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:14.860,00:51:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,cn times c0, cn times c1, cn times c2.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:17.860,00:51:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,All the way to cn times cn minus 1.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:21.860,00:51:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But we don't know if the quadrature formulas give us 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:27.860,00:51:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Is there a way we could ensure that those could be 0?
Dialogue: 0,00:51:31.860,00:51:34.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I mean, we've got this 0 there.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:34.860,00:51:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Take the points to be the roots of the nth order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:41.860,00:51:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That is, I have cn.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:43.860,00:51:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It's an nth order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:45.860,00:51:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It has terms from a0 to a0.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:47.860,00:51:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,a1 plus a1x plus a2x squared, et cetera.
Dialogue: 0,00:51:51.860,00:51:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's what we're going to have to do.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:01.860,00:52:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we want cn of xi to be equal to 0.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:05.860,00:52:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or if you write down what cn is, cn of x is equal to a0 plus a1x plus a2x squared.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:15.860,00:52:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,All the way to a to the n, x to the n.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:23.860,00:52:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're going to take this polynomial and we're going to find its n roots.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:33.860,00:52:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or its n xi's.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:43.860,00:52:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's what we're going to do.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:45.860,00:52:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If we do that, it means we've satisfied the higher order terms immediately.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:55.860,00:52:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We don't have to do anything.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:57.860,00:52:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It says, here's our quadrature scheme.
Dialogue: 0,00:52:59.860,00:53:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We've got n weights.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:01.860,00:53:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It doesn't matter what the weights are.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:03.860,00:53:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,As long as we use these n points, these roots of the nth order orthogonal polynomial,
Dialogue: 0,00:53:09.860,00:53:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as our evaluation points,
Dialogue: 0,00:53:11.860,00:53:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then I don't care what the weights are.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:13.860,00:53:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I'll always satisfy the higher order and exactness constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:19.860,00:53:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,For free.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:21.860,00:53:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Amazing.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:23.860,00:53:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, I thought it was amazing.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:25.860,00:53:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Remember, learning this from the first time I was a staff member.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:29.860,00:53:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Who thought of this?
Dialogue: 0,00:53:31.860,00:53:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:33.860,00:53:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Who thought of almost everything.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:35.860,00:53:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So,
Dialogue: 0,00:53:37.860,00:53:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,how do we figure out what the weights are?
Dialogue: 0,00:53:41.860,00:53:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What's the weight of the sum?
Dialogue: 0,00:53:43.860,00:53:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Does it matter what the weights are?
Dialogue: 0,00:53:45.860,00:53:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Can we use any weights?
Dialogue: 0,00:53:47.860,00:53:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It doesn't matter what we pick for the weights.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:51.860,00:53:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're always satisfying the higher order constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:53.860,00:53:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We still have those pesky lower order constraints, though.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:57.860,00:53:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The ones having to do with c0 through cn.
Dialogue: 0,00:53:59.860,00:54:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We still have those.
Dialogue: 0,00:54:01.860,00:54:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But those,
Dialogue: 0,00:54:05.860,00:54:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because now we know where the evaluation points are,
Dialogue: 0,00:54:07.860,00:54:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we have
Dialogue: 0,00:54:09.860,00:54:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we have
Dialogue: 0,00:54:11.860,00:54:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,evaluation points
Dialogue: 0,00:54:13.860,00:54:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because we know we got them from the roots of this polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:54:17.860,00:54:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And then once we know those evaluation points,
Dialogue: 0,00:54:19.860,00:54:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we can set up the linear system
Dialogue: 0,00:54:21.860,00:54:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and solve for the weights.
Dialogue: 0,00:54:25.860,00:54:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And with these weights,
Dialogue: 0,00:54:27.860,00:54:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we'll exactly satisfy the lower order constraints.
Dialogue: 0,00:54:31.860,00:54:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So what do we do?
Dialogue: 0,00:54:33.860,00:54:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We find
Dialogue: 0,00:54:35.860,00:54:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,n orthogonal polypolis
Dialogue: 0,00:54:39.860,00:54:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and
Dialogue: 0,00:54:41.860,00:54:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we
Dialogue: 0,00:54:43.860,00:54:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we
Dialogue: 0,00:54:45.860,00:54:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the x i's
Dialogue: 0,00:54:47.860,00:54:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,equal the roots
Dialogue: 0,00:54:55.860,00:54:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the roots of c and of x
Dialogue: 0,00:54:59.860,00:55:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then the weights
Dialogue: 0,00:55:07.860,00:55:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,are picked at
Dialogue: 0,00:55:09.860,00:55:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,switch right
Dialogue: 0,00:55:11.860,00:55:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,weights from
Dialogue: 0,00:55:13.860,00:55:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,linear solve.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:21.860,00:55:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's it.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:23.860,00:55:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's all we have to do.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:25.860,00:55:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Now the question is,
Dialogue: 0,00:55:27.860,00:55:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,okay, so how do we get these orthogonal polynomials?
Dialogue: 0,00:55:29.860,00:55:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And what about this linear system?
Dialogue: 0,00:55:31.860,00:55:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Is this linear system well behaved?
Dialogue: 0,00:55:35.860,00:55:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What are the rows of this linear system?
Dialogue: 0,00:55:37.860,00:55:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What are the rows of this linear system?
Dialogue: 0,00:55:41.860,00:55:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The first row is the zeroth order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:43.860,00:55:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The second row is this
Dialogue: 0,00:55:45.860,00:55:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,zeroth order polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:55:47.860,00:55:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that formally the polynomial is orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:55:49.860,00:55:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to the zeroth order polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:51.860,00:55:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that row is like a
Dialogue: 0,00:55:53.860,00:55:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,picture of the polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:55.860,00:55:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So the second row
Dialogue: 0,00:55:57.860,00:55:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is almost orthogonal to the first.
Dialogue: 0,00:55:59.860,00:56:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And you use that to be precisely orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:56:01.860,00:56:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,with these points
Dialogue: 0,00:56:03.860,00:56:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but that's more so because
Dialogue: 0,00:56:05.860,00:56:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,each of these rows now
Dialogue: 0,00:56:07.860,00:56:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,corresponds to
Dialogue: 0,00:56:09.860,00:56:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,sampling of an orthogonal polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:11.860,00:56:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of a polynomial that's orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:56:13.860,00:56:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to the one in the row above it.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:15.860,00:56:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So this linear system is likely to be well conditioned.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:17.860,00:56:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Sorry, did you have a question?
Dialogue: 0,00:56:23.860,00:56:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So, that's it.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:25.860,00:56:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Right?
Dialogue: 0,00:56:27.860,00:56:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Did we make the problem linear?
Dialogue: 0,00:56:29.860,00:56:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I mean, when I started writing down the beginning
Dialogue: 0,00:56:31.860,00:56:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I said, well we could set up this non-linear system of equations
Dialogue: 0,00:56:33.860,00:56:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we could use Newton's method to solve it
Dialogue: 0,00:56:35.860,00:56:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and come up with the points
Dialogue: 0,00:56:37.860,00:56:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the weights. And I said that was going to be
Dialogue: 0,00:56:39.860,00:56:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,helpful to get this ill-conditioned matrix.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:41.860,00:56:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So where did that non-linear thing go?
Dialogue: 0,00:56:45.860,00:56:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Is it still here? Is the problem still non-linear?
Dialogue: 0,00:56:49.860,00:56:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Yeah?
Dialogue: 0,00:56:51.860,00:56:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I believe that it's off of the roots.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:53.860,00:56:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Yeah, it's here.
Dialogue: 0,00:56:55.860,00:56:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Alright, finding the root finding
Dialogue: 0,00:57:01.860,00:57:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is non-linear.
Dialogue: 0,00:57:03.860,00:57:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But what properties
Dialogue: 0,00:57:05.860,00:57:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,does it have that makes it very appealing
Dialogue: 0,00:57:07.860,00:57:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for us to use for
Dialogue: 0,00:57:09.860,00:57:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,our answer schemes?
Dialogue: 0,00:57:11.860,00:57:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Why is this, why is
Dialogue: 0,00:57:13.860,00:57:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,training in that big non-linear
Dialogue: 0,00:57:15.860,00:57:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,system to solve for just finding the roots
Dialogue: 0,00:57:17.860,00:57:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of a higher order polynomial
Dialogue: 0,00:57:19.860,00:57:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,a really good idea?
Dialogue: 0,00:57:21.860,00:57:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Because this is
Dialogue: 0,00:57:23.860,00:57:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,someone else's problem.
Dialogue: 0,00:57:29.860,00:57:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Right, there's a
Dialogue: 0,00:57:31.860,00:57:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you know in MATLAB they have something
Dialogue: 0,00:57:33.860,00:57:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that counts roots of polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:57:35.860,00:57:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we'll find all of them for you.
Dialogue: 0,00:57:37.860,00:57:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Yeah, there are all these, that's a little
Dialogue: 0,00:57:39.860,00:57:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,glib. It's the, what we've
Dialogue: 0,00:57:41.860,00:57:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,done is to turn our problem of calculating
Dialogue: 0,00:57:43.860,00:57:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,quadric points in weight into
Dialogue: 0,00:57:45.860,00:57:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,one for which they know how to numerically
Dialogue: 0,00:57:47.860,00:57:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,compute solutions. Roots of
Dialogue: 0,00:57:49.860,00:57:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,polynomials, and we're using that
Dialogue: 0,00:57:51.860,00:57:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to solve for our points in weight.
Dialogue: 0,00:57:53.860,00:57:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But the non-linear problem hasn't gone away.
Dialogue: 0,00:57:55.860,00:57:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It just means
Dialogue: 0,00:57:57.860,00:57:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that we have turned it into one
Dialogue: 0,00:57:59.860,00:58:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for which there is already a lot of work
Dialogue: 0,00:58:01.860,00:58:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,on making good procedures.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:03.860,00:58:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're really counting on the fact that somebody else has already
Dialogue: 0,00:58:05.860,00:58:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,solved that problem. And we just
Dialogue: 0,00:58:07.860,00:58:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,used it in this case.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:09.860,00:58:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we haven't taken the non-linear
Dialogue: 0,00:58:11.860,00:58:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,problem out.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:13.860,00:58:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We have just decomposed them.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:15.860,00:58:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we have this non-linear part of the problem
Dialogue: 0,00:58:17.860,00:58:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is encapsulated with polynomial roots
Dialogue: 0,00:58:19.860,00:58:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then we have a linear solve.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:21.860,00:58:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Is it possible that that has complex
Dialogue: 0,00:58:23.860,00:58:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,roots or would you instruct
Dialogue: 0,00:58:25.860,00:58:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,polynomials about it?
Dialogue: 0,00:58:27.860,00:58:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So the orthogonal polynomials,
Dialogue: 0,00:58:29.860,00:58:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you have to have ones for which the roots
Dialogue: 0,00:58:31.860,00:58:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,are going to be real.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:33.860,00:58:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That is an issue.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:35.860,00:58:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And if you use polynomials that are orthogonal
Dialogue: 0,00:58:37.860,00:58:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,over say
Dialogue: 0,00:58:39.860,00:58:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,an integral from minus one to one,
Dialogue: 0,00:58:41.860,00:58:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,like the Chebyshev polynomials, those roots are always real.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:43.860,00:58:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But yeah,
Dialogue: 0,00:58:45.860,00:58:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the orthogonal polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:47.860,00:58:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,There are some ways in which when you
Dialogue: 0,00:58:49.860,00:58:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,set up orthogonal polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:58:51.860,00:58:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can guarantee that they're real roots.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:53.860,00:58:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But that's the idea.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:55.860,00:58:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're going to construct these n plus one orthogonal polynomials.
Dialogue: 0,00:58:57.860,00:58:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're going to compute the roots of the nth
Dialogue: 0,00:58:59.860,00:59:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of a polynomial so that
Dialogue: 0,00:59:01.860,00:59:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,c of n of x i is equal to zero.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:03.860,00:59:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We'll solve the linear system for the weights
Dialogue: 0,00:59:05.860,00:59:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then we'll approximate the integral as the sum.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:07.860,00:59:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So
Dialogue: 0,00:59:09.860,00:59:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it's a great method
Dialogue: 0,00:59:11.860,00:59:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you have a lot of degrees of freedom
Dialogue: 0,00:59:13.860,00:59:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,about how you do the orthogonal polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:59:15.860,00:59:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because we use just one definition of orthogonality.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:17.860,00:59:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But you can come up with all sorts of different schemes
Dialogue: 0,00:59:19.860,00:59:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,by changing what we mean by an orthogonal polynomial.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:21.860,00:59:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that says the inner product of two polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:59:23.860,00:59:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,integrated over the integral is zero.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:25.860,00:59:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We could pick different intervals.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:27.860,00:59:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We could pick a weighting function
Dialogue: 0,00:59:29.860,00:59:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that sits in the middle of it.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:31.860,00:59:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And then we can say
Dialogue: 0,00:59:33.860,00:59:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that the integral is zero.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:35.860,00:59:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that's the idea.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:37.860,00:59:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that's the idea.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:39.860,00:59:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And you get things like Gauss-Lobato,
Dialogue: 0,00:59:41.860,00:59:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss-Chebyshev,
Dialogue: 0,00:59:43.860,00:59:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss-Legendre, all these different ones
Dialogue: 0,00:59:45.860,00:59:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that have to do with different intervals
Dialogue: 0,00:59:47.860,00:59:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and different representations
Dialogue: 0,00:59:49.860,00:59:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of the inner product.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:51.860,00:59:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But they all come down to the same thing.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:53.860,00:59:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You have to find the roots of the orthogonal polynomials
Dialogue: 0,00:59:55.860,00:59:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but you get to play with what orthogonality is.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:57.860,00:59:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or to come up with a weighted orthogonality.
Dialogue: 0,00:59:59.860,01:00:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or to come up with a weighted orthogonality.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:01.860,01:00:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or to come up with a weighted orthogonality.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:03.860,01:00:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So an endpoint
Dialogue: 0,01:00:05.860,01:00:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss-Wagner method
Dialogue: 0,01:00:07.860,01:00:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is exact for polynomials up to order two n.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:09.860,01:00:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is exact for orthogonality up to order two n.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:11.860,01:00:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And that means the thing goes
Dialogue: 0,01:00:13.860,01:00:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,what we refer to as spectrally accurate.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:15.860,01:00:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And that's how you get the meaning
Dialogue: 0,01:00:17.860,01:00:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that is you add more points.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:19.860,01:00:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If we're looking at something like
Dialogue: 0,01:00:21.860,01:00:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the simple
Dialogue: 0,01:00:23.860,01:00:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Poitier scheme of using the midpoint rule
Dialogue: 0,01:00:25.860,01:00:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,this one has an error
Dialogue: 0,01:00:27.860,01:00:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that's proportional to one over n squared.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:29.860,01:00:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If I double the number of points
Dialogue: 0,01:00:31.860,01:00:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I'll get something like four times
Dialogue: 0,01:00:33.860,01:00:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as much accuracy.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:35.860,01:00:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Or four times the reduction of the error.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:37.860,01:00:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But these methods are
Dialogue: 0,01:00:39.860,01:00:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,more accurate.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:41.860,01:00:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Now we come back to the point I put up
Dialogue: 0,01:00:43.860,01:00:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,at the beginning, at the earlier,
Dialogue: 0,01:00:45.860,01:00:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which is this is doing the cosine.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:47.860,01:00:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,This is the Gauss-Chebyshev
Dialogue: 0,01:00:49.860,01:00:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,This is the Gauss-Chebyshev
Dialogue: 0,01:00:51.860,01:00:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is the one I used for here.
Dialogue: 0,01:00:53.860,01:00:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Even though Gauss-Wagner
Dialogue: 0,01:00:55.860,01:00:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is using Chebyshev polynomials
Dialogue: 0,01:00:57.860,01:00:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is using Chebyshev polynomials
Dialogue: 0,01:00:59.860,01:01:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which look a little like sines and cosines.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:01.860,01:01:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And I just remind you
Dialogue: 0,01:01:03.860,01:01:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that with 11 points
Dialogue: 0,01:01:05.860,01:01:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can get machine precision out of these methods.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:07.860,01:01:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And you can almost see that each time
Dialogue: 0,01:01:09.860,01:01:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you add one more point
Dialogue: 0,01:01:11.860,01:01:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you get errors that
Dialogue: 0,01:01:13.860,01:01:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,double on each additional point.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:15.860,01:01:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that's the characteristic
Dialogue: 0,01:01:17.860,01:01:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of spectral accuracy.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:19.860,01:01:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So any linear accuracy will give you
Dialogue: 0,01:01:21.860,01:01:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,a straight line on the Y-Law curve
Dialogue: 0,01:01:23.860,01:01:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and spectral accuracy means it's going down.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:25.860,01:01:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So it's going even faster than a straight line.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:27.860,01:01:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,There's no straight line with any slope
Dialogue: 0,01:01:29.860,01:01:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that will fit.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:31.860,01:01:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Then another thing to look at is
Dialogue: 0,01:01:33.860,01:01:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,well suppose we took this interval
Dialogue: 0,01:01:35.860,01:01:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from minus one to one
Dialogue: 0,01:01:37.860,01:01:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and looked to see where the simple Poitier points are
Dialogue: 0,01:01:39.860,01:01:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which are these intervals
Dialogue: 0,01:01:41.860,01:01:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,versus the Gauss-Claude points.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:43.860,01:01:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You can look at it and say
Dialogue: 0,01:01:45.860,01:01:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,well, they're not that different.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:47.860,01:01:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But they are.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:49.860,01:01:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You can see, and this is what's characteristic
Dialogue: 0,01:01:51.860,01:01:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of many of these quadrature schemes
Dialogue: 0,01:01:53.860,01:01:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,notice they're squeezed together at the ends
Dialogue: 0,01:01:55.860,01:01:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and spread out in the middle.
Dialogue: 0,01:01:59.860,01:02:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So
Dialogue: 0,01:02:01.860,01:02:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it's a small, it looks like a small thing
Dialogue: 0,01:02:03.860,01:02:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I mean you're moving them around
Dialogue: 0,01:02:05.860,01:02:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the weights are
Dialogue: 0,01:02:07.860,01:02:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,not that non-uniform either.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:09.860,01:02:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But they don't change that much.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:11.860,01:02:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,When we're talking about these high accuracy calculations
Dialogue: 0,01:02:13.860,01:02:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,these kinds of small differences
Dialogue: 0,01:02:15.860,01:02:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,make an enormous difference.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:17.860,01:02:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're not looking to get one percent accuracy
Dialogue: 0,01:02:19.860,01:02:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or point one percent accuracy.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:21.860,01:02:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If you are then midpoint rule is fine.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:23.860,01:02:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If you're looking for much higher accuracy
Dialogue: 0,01:02:25.860,01:02:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,close to machine precision
Dialogue: 0,01:02:27.860,01:02:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then these things make an enormous amount of difference
Dialogue: 0,01:02:29.860,01:02:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and even small changes
Dialogue: 0,01:02:31.860,01:02:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,like this point placement
Dialogue: 0,01:02:33.860,01:02:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the changes in the weights can make an enormous difference.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:35.860,01:02:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Alright, so
Dialogue: 0,01:02:37.860,01:02:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I'm going to
Dialogue: 0,01:02:39.860,01:02:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we talked about this Gauss quadrature scheme
Dialogue: 0,01:02:41.860,01:02:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and these are great methods
Dialogue: 0,01:02:43.860,01:02:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we're going to see next time
Dialogue: 0,01:02:45.860,01:02:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the reason we're looking at them
Dialogue: 0,01:02:47.860,01:02:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is because we can actually turn them into a method
Dialogue: 0,01:02:49.860,01:02:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for solving integral equations
Dialogue: 0,01:02:51.860,01:02:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,in some settings.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:53.860,01:02:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But not all of them
Dialogue: 0,01:02:55.860,01:02:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and not the most common one in 3D
Dialogue: 0,01:02:57.860,01:02:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which are these panel methods I talked about in the first lecture.
Dialogue: 0,01:02:59.860,01:03:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So remember what our problem was
Dialogue: 0,01:03:01.860,01:03:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for a panel method.
Dialogue: 0,01:03:03.860,01:03:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're calculating these panels
Dialogue: 0,01:03:05.860,01:03:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,under which we're going to assume a constant density
Dialogue: 0,01:03:07.860,01:03:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and if we're doing a collocation method
Dialogue: 0,01:03:09.860,01:03:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or a Lurkin method
Dialogue: 0,01:03:11.860,01:03:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we have to calculate these integrals
Dialogue: 0,01:03:13.860,01:03:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of one over distance over this panel
Dialogue: 0,01:03:15.860,01:03:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for a point on the panel
Dialogue: 0,01:03:17.860,01:03:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which means somewhere in that panel
Dialogue: 0,01:03:19.860,01:03:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the integrand goes to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:03:21.860,01:03:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,This is what's called a singular integral.
Dialogue: 0,01:03:23.860,01:03:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we knew from last time
Dialogue: 0,01:03:25.860,01:03:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we knew it was an integral singularity
Dialogue: 0,01:03:27.860,01:03:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we did that by carving out a disc out of it
Dialogue: 0,01:03:29.860,01:03:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to prove it.
Dialogue: 0,01:03:31.860,01:03:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But for this problem
Dialogue: 0,01:03:33.860,01:03:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,those quadrature schemes aren't going to happen.
Dialogue: 0,01:03:35.860,01:03:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So
Dialogue: 0,01:03:37.860,01:03:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I want to
Dialogue: 0,01:03:39.860,01:03:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,show you what happens here.
Dialogue: 0,01:03:41.860,01:03:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So if we do something like one over the
Dialogue: 0,01:03:43.860,01:03:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,square root of the absolute value of x
Dialogue: 0,01:03:45.860,01:03:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and try to do a quadrature scheme
Dialogue: 0,01:03:47.860,01:03:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as long as we keep away from the
Dialogue: 0,01:03:49.860,01:03:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,quadrature points
Dialogue: 0,01:03:51.860,01:03:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,at exactly x equals 0
Dialogue: 0,01:03:53.860,01:03:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we can still formally do the quadrature
Dialogue: 0,01:03:55.860,01:03:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,no points at x equals 0
Dialogue: 0,01:03:57.860,01:03:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so we have to pick up a polynomial
Dialogue: 0,01:03:59.860,01:04:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that gives us for whom the root is not 0.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:03.860,01:04:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But we don't get very good convergence
Dialogue: 0,01:04:05.860,01:04:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that is
Dialogue: 0,01:04:07.860,01:04:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the reason we don't is this thing goes off
Dialogue: 0,01:04:09.860,01:04:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we don't get infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:11.860,01:04:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But I want to make a point about the difference
Dialogue: 0,01:04:13.860,01:04:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,between two types of infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:15.860,01:04:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So there's one over the square root of the absolute value of x
Dialogue: 0,01:04:17.860,01:04:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,versus one over x.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:19.860,01:04:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So the one over the square root
Dialogue: 0,01:04:21.860,01:04:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of the absolute value of x
Dialogue: 0,01:04:23.860,01:04:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that is an integrable singularity.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:25.860,01:04:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The area under the curve is finite
Dialogue: 0,01:04:27.860,01:04:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,even though the integrand goes to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:29.860,01:04:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And the one over x case
Dialogue: 0,01:04:31.860,01:04:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,in one dimension
Dialogue: 0,01:04:33.860,01:04:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that goes to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:35.860,01:04:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Now it doesn't go to infinity in two dimensions
Dialogue: 0,01:04:37.860,01:04:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but it does in one dimension.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:39.860,01:04:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,There's no quadrature scheme
Dialogue: 0,01:04:43.860,01:04:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that can give you
Dialogue: 0,01:04:45.860,01:04:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that can solve this problem.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:47.860,01:04:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If your integral is infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:04:49.860,01:04:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,here's your integral.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:51.860,01:04:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:53.860,01:04:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's it.
Dialogue: 0,01:04:55.860,01:04:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If it has an integrable singularity
Dialogue: 0,01:04:57.860,01:04:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then
Dialogue: 0,01:04:59.860,01:05:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,maybe a quadrature scheme would help you
Dialogue: 0,01:05:01.860,01:05:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,except what's true about that problem?
Dialogue: 0,01:05:05.860,01:05:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,When we started doing these quadrature error estimates
Dialogue: 0,01:05:07.860,01:05:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,what thing did we count on?
Dialogue: 0,01:05:09.860,01:05:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,In order to say something about the error.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:11.860,01:05:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We used the
Dialogue: 0,01:05:13.860,01:05:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,remainder theorem for the Taylor series
Dialogue: 0,01:05:15.860,01:05:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which counted on what about the derivatives?
Dialogue: 0,01:05:19.860,01:05:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Was the Taylor series expansion derivatives?
Dialogue: 0,01:05:21.860,01:05:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:23.860,01:05:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Yeah but these
Dialogue: 0,01:05:25.860,01:05:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the derivatives of the integrand
Dialogue: 0,01:05:27.860,01:05:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,are going to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:29.860,01:05:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,All those quadrature estimates of the error
Dialogue: 0,01:05:31.860,01:05:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,they're pretty much worthless here.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:33.860,01:05:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So
Dialogue: 0,01:05:35.860,01:05:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you might think well okay
Dialogue: 0,01:05:37.860,01:05:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we spent a class on these quadrature schemes
Dialogue: 0,01:05:39.860,01:05:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then at the end of the class I tell you
Dialogue: 0,01:05:41.860,01:05:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for the integrals you most likely see
Dialogue: 0,01:05:43.860,01:05:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,when you're doing these integral equation methods
Dialogue: 0,01:05:45.860,01:05:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can't use these schemes.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:47.860,01:05:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well that's not entirely true
Dialogue: 0,01:05:49.860,01:05:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because there's only one panel
Dialogue: 0,01:05:51.860,01:05:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you have to worry about.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:53.860,01:05:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The panel with the test point on the panel.
Dialogue: 0,01:05:55.860,01:05:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,All the other panels that interact with this panel
Dialogue: 0,01:05:57.860,01:05:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can do those with quadrature
Dialogue: 0,01:05:59.860,01:06:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and it works great there.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:01.860,01:06:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So if I have a discretization with n panels
Dialogue: 0,01:06:03.860,01:06:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then I've got to do n squared interactions
Dialogue: 0,01:06:05.860,01:06:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and only order n of them
Dialogue: 0,01:06:07.860,01:06:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is problematic.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:09.860,01:06:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you can do Gauss quadrature
Dialogue: 0,01:06:11.860,01:06:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and do a great job of n squared minus n
Dialogue: 0,01:06:13.860,01:06:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of the panels and the n panels that you can't do that with
Dialogue: 0,01:06:15.860,01:06:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you have to do something else.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:17.860,01:06:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So
Dialogue: 0,01:06:19.860,01:06:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I told you something. So if n is very large
Dialogue: 0,01:06:21.860,01:06:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,like a thousand
Dialogue: 0,01:06:23.860,01:06:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then n squared is a million
Dialogue: 0,01:06:25.860,01:06:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and n squared minus n is almost a million.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:27.860,01:06:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I'm telling you something that works better than
Dialogue: 0,01:06:29.860,01:06:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,99% of the time
Dialogue: 0,01:06:31.860,01:06:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and that should be good enough.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:33.860,01:06:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But of course if you have to solve these problems
Dialogue: 0,01:06:35.860,01:06:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,they're still stuck with what to do for the self-charge.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:37.860,01:06:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So
Dialogue: 0,01:06:39.860,01:06:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the problem is that
Dialogue: 0,01:06:41.860,01:06:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,simple quadrature done on these
Dialogue: 0,01:06:43.860,01:06:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,problems that have singular
Dialogue: 0,01:06:45.860,01:06:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,integrands are usually better than
Dialogue: 0,01:06:47.860,01:06:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss quadrature.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:49.860,01:06:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Doing the special placement of points and weights
Dialogue: 0,01:06:51.860,01:06:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,doesn't help you at all in setting.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:53.860,01:06:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You need to do something else.
Dialogue: 0,01:06:55.860,01:06:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to take a little time
Dialogue: 0,01:06:57.860,01:06:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,at the end and I'm going to talk a little bit about what people do
Dialogue: 0,01:06:59.860,01:07:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,now.
Dialogue: 0,01:07:01.860,01:07:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I want to show you some of the
Dialogue: 0,01:07:03.860,01:07:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,standard things people try.
Dialogue: 0,01:07:05.860,01:07:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So here's one way of dealing with the problem.
Dialogue: 0,01:07:07.860,01:07:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You say, okay, well, look, I can do Gauss quadrature
Dialogue: 0,01:07:09.860,01:07:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so if I imagine I have a panel
Dialogue: 0,01:07:11.860,01:07:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I want to
Dialogue: 0,01:07:13.860,01:07:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so
Dialogue: 0,01:07:15.860,01:07:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so imagine
Dialogue: 0,01:07:17.860,01:07:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,this is my panel and I want to integrate
Dialogue: 0,01:07:19.860,01:07:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,1 over r and the problem is that
Dialogue: 0,01:07:21.860,01:07:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the 1 over r, the 1 over distance on the panel
Dialogue: 0,01:07:23.860,01:07:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it goes to infinity at the center.
Dialogue: 0,01:07:25.860,01:07:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to do my
Dialogue: 0,01:07:27.860,01:07:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss quadrature scheme
Dialogue: 0,01:07:31.860,01:07:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,on this region
Dialogue: 0,01:07:33.860,01:07:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and then
Dialogue: 0,01:07:35.860,01:07:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I'll do something else in the interior.
Dialogue: 0,01:07:37.860,01:07:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And I might, you know, because it's hard
Dialogue: 0,01:07:39.860,01:07:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to do this region, I could
Dialogue: 0,01:07:41.860,01:07:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,tear out a square out of it
Dialogue: 0,01:07:43.860,01:07:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so it has, you know,
Dialogue: 0,01:07:45.860,01:07:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the geometry is nice and I can do
Dialogue: 0,01:07:47.860,01:07:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Gauss quadrature on these nice square integrals
Dialogue: 0,01:07:49.860,01:07:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,where it's
Dialogue: 0,01:07:51.860,01:07:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,easy to do so.
Dialogue: 0,01:07:53.860,01:07:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So, alright, that's
Dialogue: 0,01:07:55.860,01:07:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,better. I just have to pull out
Dialogue: 0,01:07:57.860,01:07:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I just have to figure out what to do with this little square in the center
Dialogue: 0,01:07:59.860,01:08:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I say, well,
Dialogue: 0,01:08:01.860,01:08:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,okay, but I haven't removed the problem.
Dialogue: 0,01:08:03.860,01:08:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I just figured, well, look,
Dialogue: 0,01:08:05.860,01:08:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it's a much smaller contribution to the integral
Dialogue: 0,01:08:07.860,01:08:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so if I screw it up, it won't have as bad
Dialogue: 0,01:08:09.860,01:08:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,an impact. You say, well, okay,
Dialogue: 0,01:08:11.860,01:08:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but you're still screwing it up.
Dialogue: 0,01:08:13.860,01:08:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you take this one
Dialogue: 0,01:08:15.860,01:08:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you say, alright, well, I blow
Dialogue: 0,01:08:17.860,01:08:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,this square up into another square and I take
Dialogue: 0,01:08:19.860,01:08:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,out a little piece. So I start by
Dialogue: 0,01:08:21.860,01:08:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,taking out one piece and then I
Dialogue: 0,01:08:23.860,01:08:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,go inside and take out another piece
Dialogue: 0,01:08:25.860,01:08:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and another piece. You do that
Dialogue: 0,01:08:27.860,01:08:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,a few times. These are sometimes
Dialogue: 0,01:08:29.860,01:08:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,called refinement strategies.
Dialogue: 0,01:08:31.860,01:08:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So people do this kind of thing where they
Dialogue: 0,01:08:33.860,01:08:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,try to deal with the singularity by
Dialogue: 0,01:08:35.860,01:08:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,taking out smaller
Dialogue: 0,01:08:37.860,01:08:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and smaller regions of the domain you're trying to integrate
Dialogue: 0,01:08:39.860,01:08:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and do the rest of it with the
Dialogue: 0,01:08:41.860,01:08:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,regular quadrature scheme and
Dialogue: 0,01:08:43.860,01:08:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,really just the region right around the
Dialogue: 0,01:08:45.860,01:08:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,singularity with something else or with
Dialogue: 0,01:08:47.860,01:08:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,a lower scheme.
Dialogue: 0,01:08:49.860,01:08:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So those work alright. They're not great and
Dialogue: 0,01:08:51.860,01:08:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,often pretty expensive.
Dialogue: 0,01:08:53.860,01:08:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,The other one that's very
Dialogue: 0,01:08:55.860,01:08:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,popular is find the change
Dialogue: 0,01:08:57.860,01:08:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of variables. So
Dialogue: 0,01:08:59.860,01:09:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,sometimes if you know what the function is,
Dialogue: 0,01:09:01.860,01:09:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,maybe the change of variables,
Dialogue: 0,01:09:03.860,01:09:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if you put the integral in front of the change of variables,
Dialogue: 0,01:09:05.860,01:09:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then you get rid of the singularity.
Dialogue: 0,01:09:07.860,01:09:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that's really popular
Dialogue: 0,01:09:09.860,01:09:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,too.
Dialogue: 0,01:09:11.860,01:09:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Though if you're
Dialogue: 0,01:09:13.860,01:09:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,functioning and trying to integrate,
Dialogue: 0,01:09:15.860,01:09:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if you can come up with that change of variables,
Dialogue: 0,01:09:17.860,01:09:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then great.
Dialogue: 0,01:09:19.860,01:09:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,One over r, one over distance?
Dialogue: 0,01:09:21.860,01:09:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,No. There's no nice
Dialogue: 0,01:09:23.860,01:09:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,change of variables that will do that.
Dialogue: 0,01:09:25.860,01:09:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But there are some things you can do.
Dialogue: 0,01:09:27.860,01:09:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you
Dialogue: 0,01:09:29.860,01:09:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,have all these kinds of schemes
Dialogue: 0,01:09:31.860,01:09:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and if you go
Dialogue: 0,01:09:33.860,01:09:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,through the literature you can find
Dialogue: 0,01:09:35.860,01:09:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,literally thousands of papers
Dialogue: 0,01:09:37.860,01:09:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,where they say, okay,
Dialogue: 0,01:09:39.860,01:09:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we're going to do a quadrature scheme
Dialogue: 0,01:09:41.860,01:09:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,where we're going to use polynomials with
Dialogue: 0,01:09:43.860,01:09:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,an inner product where the singularity
Dialogue: 0,01:09:45.860,01:09:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is in the inner product definition
Dialogue: 0,01:09:47.860,01:09:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and that's going to work for this kind of singularity
Dialogue: 0,01:09:49.860,01:09:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and there's some papers that can deal with
Dialogue: 0,01:09:51.860,01:09:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,singularities that correspond to a point
Dialogue: 0,01:09:53.860,01:09:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,in the center and one at a point in the
Dialogue: 0,01:09:55.860,01:09:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,corner and one at a point along the edge.
Dialogue: 0,01:09:57.860,01:09:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You have all these different things that you can do.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:01.860,01:10:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And it's figured out
Dialogue: 0,01:10:07.860,01:10:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that there's something else you can do
Dialogue: 0,01:10:09.860,01:10:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,in that case.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:11.860,01:10:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So I'm going to show you a picture
Dialogue: 0,01:10:13.860,01:10:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of what you do.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:15.860,01:10:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So let's imagine that we're doing
Dialogue: 0,01:10:17.860,01:10:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,this integral from zero to one
Dialogue: 0,01:10:19.860,01:10:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of one over the square root of
Dialogue: 0,01:10:21.860,01:10:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the absolute value of x.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:23.860,01:10:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we know if we plot
Dialogue: 0,01:10:25.860,01:10:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that one over the square root
Dialogue: 0,01:10:27.860,01:10:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of the absolute value of x
Dialogue: 0,01:10:29.860,01:10:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as a function of x,
Dialogue: 0,01:10:31.860,01:10:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you know, when x is large
Dialogue: 0,01:10:33.860,01:10:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it's fine, you know,
Dialogue: 0,01:10:35.860,01:10:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because x gets bigger,
Dialogue: 0,01:10:37.860,01:10:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it goes down slowly,
Dialogue: 0,01:10:39.860,01:10:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and it blows up near the origin.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:41.860,01:10:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So this is our problem.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:43.860,01:10:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Right?
Dialogue: 0,01:10:47.860,01:10:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we don't care about the rest of this integral,
Dialogue: 0,01:10:49.860,01:10:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we want to do something about this.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:51.860,01:10:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So,
Dialogue: 0,01:10:53.860,01:10:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the idea is to come up with
Dialogue: 0,01:10:55.860,01:10:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so we'll call this f.
Dialogue: 0,01:10:57.860,01:10:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And we're going to come up with
Dialogue: 0,01:10:59.860,01:11:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,a new integral
Dialogue: 0,01:11:01.860,01:11:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which is going to be integrated from
Dialogue: 0,01:11:03.860,01:11:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,instead of from zero to one,
Dialogue: 0,01:11:05.860,01:11:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it's going to go from
Dialogue: 0,01:11:07.860,01:11:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,minus infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:11:09.860,01:11:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to one.
Dialogue: 0,01:11:11.860,01:11:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, actually they usually do ones that go
Dialogue: 0,01:11:13.860,01:11:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from minus infinity to plus infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:11:15.860,01:11:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Where you're going to come up with
Dialogue: 0,01:11:17.860,01:11:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,some function g of t
Dialogue: 0,01:11:21.860,01:11:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we'll use the change of variables one to one
Dialogue: 0,01:11:23.860,01:11:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,where g of t
Dialogue: 0,01:11:27.860,01:11:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is going to be
Dialogue: 0,01:11:29.860,01:11:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,when t is equal to
Dialogue: 0,01:11:31.860,01:11:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:11:33.860,01:11:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,g of t equals one
Dialogue: 0,01:11:37.860,01:11:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and when t is equal to minus infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:11:39.860,01:11:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,g of t is equal to minus one.
Dialogue: 0,01:11:41.860,01:11:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we're going to take this function
Dialogue: 0,01:11:43.860,01:11:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we're going to try to
Dialogue: 0,01:11:45.860,01:11:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,expand it out
Dialogue: 0,01:11:47.860,01:11:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,over this infinite domain.
Dialogue: 0,01:11:49.860,01:11:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,We're now going to have it go from
Dialogue: 0,01:11:51.860,01:11:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,minus infinity to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:11:53.860,01:11:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So that we put this thing
Dialogue: 0,01:11:55.860,01:11:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that's going off to infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:11:57.860,01:11:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,out at the infinite interval
Dialogue: 0,01:11:59.860,01:12:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you might think,
Dialogue: 0,01:12:01.860,01:12:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,well, what the heck
Dialogue: 0,01:12:03.860,01:12:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is this going to do?
Dialogue: 0,01:12:05.860,01:12:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, it's going to go from
Dialogue: 0,01:12:07.860,01:12:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,minus infinity to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:12:09.860,01:12:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,What the heck is this going to do?
Dialogue: 0,01:12:11.860,01:12:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So we now have this problem
Dialogue: 0,01:12:13.860,01:12:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we've replaced
Dialogue: 0,01:12:15.860,01:12:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,this integral from zero to one
Dialogue: 0,01:12:17.860,01:12:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,with an integral from
Dialogue: 0,01:12:19.860,01:12:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,minus infinity to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:12:21.860,01:12:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you look at that
Dialogue: 0,01:12:23.860,01:12:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you think, well, that can't possibly
Dialogue: 0,01:12:25.860,01:12:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,be a good idea.
Dialogue: 0,01:12:27.860,01:12:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, it turns out
Dialogue: 0,01:12:35.860,01:12:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I'll put a reference on it
Dialogue: 0,01:12:37.860,01:12:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because these have become
Dialogue: 0,01:12:39.860,01:12:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,very common now.
Dialogue: 0,01:12:45.860,01:12:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,If you have a function that looks like that
Dialogue: 0,01:12:47.860,01:12:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as long as
Dialogue: 0,01:12:49.860,01:12:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,this function g prime of t
Dialogue: 0,01:12:51.860,01:12:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,goes to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:12:53.860,01:12:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,faster than
Dialogue: 0,01:12:55.860,01:12:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,your original function goes to infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:12:57.860,01:12:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,then the product
Dialogue: 0,01:12:59.860,01:13:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of f of g of t
Dialogue: 0,01:13:01.860,01:13:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,times
Dialogue: 0,01:13:03.860,01:13:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,g prime of t
Dialogue: 0,01:13:05.860,01:13:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can arrange for it to look like this
Dialogue: 0,01:13:07.860,01:13:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as we go from minus infinity to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:13:09.860,01:13:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So if we look at this function
Dialogue: 0,01:13:11.860,01:13:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as a function of t
Dialogue: 0,01:13:13.860,01:13:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,if you can arrange it
Dialogue: 0,01:13:15.860,01:13:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so that this thing goes to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:13:17.860,01:13:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,smoothly
Dialogue: 0,01:13:19.860,01:13:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it has to go to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:13:21.860,01:13:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,fast.
Dialogue: 0,01:13:23.860,01:13:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So if you look at this
Dialogue: 0,01:13:25.860,01:13:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,function
Dialogue: 0,01:13:27.860,01:13:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as a function of t
Dialogue: 0,01:13:29.860,01:13:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it has to go to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:13:31.860,01:13:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,fast.
Dialogue: 0,01:13:33.860,01:13:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So if you look at this
Dialogue: 0,01:13:35.860,01:13:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,function
Dialogue: 0,01:13:37.860,01:13:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as a function of t
Dialogue: 0,01:13:39.860,01:13:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it has to go to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:13:41.860,01:13:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and infinitely differentiable.
Dialogue: 0,01:13:47.860,01:13:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you know what these functions look like?
Dialogue: 0,01:13:49.860,01:13:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,They're hyperbolic sines and cosines
Dialogue: 0,01:13:51.860,01:13:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and tangents.
Dialogue: 0,01:13:53.860,01:13:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,One of those things you learned in high school geometry
Dialogue: 0,01:13:55.860,01:13:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you thought, well, I'm never going to use those again.
Dialogue: 0,01:13:57.860,01:13:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,They're back.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:01.860,01:14:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So you can come up with functions
Dialogue: 0,01:14:03.860,01:14:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that will do this
Dialogue: 0,01:14:05.860,01:14:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for any singularity you come up with.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:07.860,01:14:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So if you look at this function
Dialogue: 0,01:14:09.860,01:14:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,as a function of t
Dialogue: 0,01:14:11.860,01:14:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it has to go to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:14:13.860,01:14:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,smoothly
Dialogue: 0,01:14:15.860,01:14:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and fast enough
Dialogue: 0,01:14:17.860,01:14:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so that it will go to zero
Dialogue: 0,01:14:19.860,01:14:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,faster than f is going to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:21.860,01:14:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,You might say, well, wait a second.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:23.860,01:14:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Now I have to integrate
Dialogue: 0,01:14:25.860,01:14:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from minus infinity to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:27.860,01:14:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So how do I do equally spaced points
Dialogue: 0,01:14:29.860,01:14:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,from minus infinity to infinity?
Dialogue: 0,01:14:31.860,01:14:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Well, I can do midpoint rule.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:33.860,01:14:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I can put one at zero.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:35.860,01:14:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,That's one point.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:37.860,01:14:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And then I can dissect the next interval.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:39.860,01:14:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So what you do is
Dialogue: 0,01:14:41.860,01:14:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you look and say, well,
Dialogue: 0,01:14:43.860,01:14:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I don't care about the tails anymore.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:53.860,01:14:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And then you just
Dialogue: 0,01:14:55.860,01:14:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,put points in.
Dialogue: 0,01:14:57.860,01:14:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And it turns out you can actually use equally spaced methods
Dialogue: 0,01:14:59.860,01:15:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for reasons I'm not going to go into.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:01.860,01:15:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,When you just put points down
Dialogue: 0,01:15:03.860,01:15:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you figure out how much
Dialogue: 0,01:15:05.860,01:15:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of the tail you're willing to ignore
Dialogue: 0,01:15:07.860,01:15:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and what kind of procedure you need.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:09.860,01:15:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And then you spread equally spaced points
Dialogue: 0,01:15:11.860,01:15:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,over the rest of the interval
Dialogue: 0,01:15:13.860,01:15:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or you do your Gauss-Cogitore points
Dialogue: 0,01:15:15.860,01:15:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and do whatever you want in that interval
Dialogue: 0,01:15:17.860,01:15:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because in this interval
Dialogue: 0,01:15:19.860,01:15:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,everything's smooth.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:21.860,01:15:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Nothing goes to infinity.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:23.860,01:15:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And you might think, how could that possibly
Dialogue: 0,01:15:25.860,01:15:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,be the best way of doing it?
Dialogue: 0,01:15:27.860,01:15:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And it turns out
Dialogue: 0,01:15:29.860,01:15:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,when you try all these schemes
Dialogue: 0,01:15:31.860,01:15:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for putting down points and weights
Dialogue: 0,01:15:33.860,01:15:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the best thing to do is to come up with
Dialogue: 0,01:15:35.860,01:15:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,things that are infinitely differentiable.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:37.860,01:15:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Things like e to the minus t squared
Dialogue: 0,01:15:39.860,01:15:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the error function
Dialogue: 0,01:15:41.860,01:15:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or that's the derivative of the error function
Dialogue: 0,01:15:43.860,01:15:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,or hyperbolic sines, cosines, and tangents
Dialogue: 0,01:15:45.860,01:15:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can use to construct these things.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:47.860,01:15:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,And that's what most of the good quadruped schemes
Dialogue: 0,01:15:49.860,01:15:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to deal with the singularity are.
Dialogue: 0,01:15:51.860,01:15:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,It seems very counterintuitive at the beginning
Dialogue: 0,01:15:53.860,01:15:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,which is why only recently
Dialogue: 0,01:15:55.860,01:15:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it has become popular
Dialogue: 0,01:15:57.860,01:15:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because you think, how could that be the right way to do it?
Dialogue: 0,01:15:59.860,01:16:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,But when you're done you end up with
Dialogue: 0,01:16:01.860,01:16:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,methods that use a few dozen points
Dialogue: 0,01:16:03.860,01:16:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you do these singular integrals
Dialogue: 0,01:16:05.860,01:16:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you can do it very visually.
Dialogue: 0,01:16:07.860,01:16:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,Yeah, my sorry, it looked like you had a question.
Dialogue: 0,01:16:09.860,01:16:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,No, no, no, I'll correct you.
Dialogue: 0,01:16:11.860,01:16:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,So, I'm going to stop there.
Dialogue: 0,01:16:13.860,01:16:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I wanted to sort of throw this in at the end
Dialogue: 0,01:16:15.860,01:16:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because it's only in the last few years
Dialogue: 0,01:16:17.860,01:16:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that these methods have started to become popular
Dialogue: 0,01:16:19.860,01:16:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I'm afraid, you know, I fell into that same category
Dialogue: 0,01:16:21.860,01:16:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of people who said, no, come on
Dialogue: 0,01:16:23.860,01:16:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we're not really going to take an integral from 0 to 1
Dialogue: 0,01:16:25.860,01:16:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and turn it into 1 from minus infinity to infinity
Dialogue: 0,01:16:27.860,01:16:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that can't be a good idea
Dialogue: 0,01:16:29.860,01:16:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but as people have gone through
Dialogue: 0,01:16:31.860,01:16:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and made practical implementations of these methods
Dialogue: 0,01:16:33.860,01:16:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and you look at the number of points in which
Dialogue: 0,01:16:35.860,01:16:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,they have to use and how generally they can be developed
Dialogue: 0,01:16:37.860,01:16:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you find that they're
Dialogue: 0,01:16:39.860,01:16:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,quite effective methods
Dialogue: 0,01:16:41.860,01:16:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and they're now good pieces of software
Dialogue: 0,01:16:43.860,01:16:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that can do these kinds of transformations
Dialogue: 0,01:16:45.860,01:16:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and let you do singular integrals
Dialogue: 0,01:16:47.860,01:16:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,though you do have to arrange
Dialogue: 0,01:16:49.860,01:16:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to put the point where the singularity is
Dialogue: 0,01:16:51.860,01:16:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,at the end of your integral
Dialogue: 0,01:16:53.860,01:16:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so if we have a panel
Dialogue: 0,01:16:55.860,01:16:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we have a singularity in the center
Dialogue: 0,01:16:57.860,01:16:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,we've got to break it up into four panels
Dialogue: 0,01:16:59.860,01:17:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so that the singularity can be at the corner
Dialogue: 0,01:17:01.860,01:17:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so there's some issues
Dialogue: 0,01:17:03.860,01:17:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,I wanted to at least show you this
Dialogue: 0,01:17:05.860,01:17:07.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,in one of the papers that gives a good survey
Dialogue: 0,01:17:07.860,01:17:09.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,of these kinds of methods and pointers to software
Dialogue: 0,01:17:09.860,01:17:11.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,so you can see
Dialogue: 0,01:17:11.860,01:17:13.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but I wanted to show you at least at the end of this
Dialogue: 0,01:17:13.860,01:17:15.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,that there are ways of dealing with singular integrals
Dialogue: 0,01:17:15.860,01:17:17.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but what we're going to do next time
Dialogue: 0,01:17:17.860,01:17:19.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,is look at problems to which we don't get singular integrals
Dialogue: 0,01:17:19.860,01:17:21.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and we'll do that next time
Dialogue: 0,01:17:21.860,01:17:23.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but for this I just wanted to show you
Dialogue: 0,01:17:23.860,01:17:25.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,what's the most modern thing
Dialogue: 0,01:17:25.860,01:17:27.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,even if we did it vaguely at the end
Dialogue: 0,01:17:27.860,01:17:29.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the big thing to remember about orthogonal polynomials
Dialogue: 0,01:17:29.860,01:17:31.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and this idea of points and weights
Dialogue: 0,01:17:31.860,01:17:33.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,where the points are coming from a polynomial
Dialogue: 0,01:17:33.860,01:17:35.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,the zeros of a polynomial
Dialogue: 0,01:17:35.860,01:17:37.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and the weights are coming from solving a linear system
Dialogue: 0,01:17:37.860,01:17:39.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,these are very powerful techniques
Dialogue: 0,01:17:39.860,01:17:41.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,you can often construct very effective
Dialogue: 0,01:17:41.860,01:17:43.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,quadrature schemes for yourself
Dialogue: 0,01:17:43.860,01:17:45.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,by determining what's a good set of polynomials
Dialogue: 0,01:17:45.860,01:17:47.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,to use for your own problem
Dialogue: 0,01:17:47.860,01:17:49.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and as we'll see next time
Dialogue: 0,01:17:49.860,01:17:51.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,it also helps you design very good methods
Dialogue: 0,01:17:51.860,01:17:53.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,for solving integral equations in 2D
Dialogue: 0,01:17:53.860,01:17:55.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,on closed-circuit boundaries
Dialogue: 0,01:17:55.860,01:17:57.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,alright
Dialogue: 0,01:17:57.860,01:17:59.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,what I didn't talk about is multiple dimensions
Dialogue: 0,01:17:59.860,01:18:01.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,and I wasn't going to say too much about that
Dialogue: 0,01:18:01.860,01:18:03.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,because we won't be talking about that
Dialogue: 0,01:18:03.860,01:18:05.860,辉英,,0,0,0,,but I wanted to show you a few things
